#registry dESCRIPTIONs asAttributes;
<tabbed>In this example, there are two components to a tabbed interface, the tab bar (a block with a tabs attribute containing tab blocks). The second component is a block of body panels, with each panel associated with a tab. Each tab block must include a tab attribute whose value is the tag of the body block associated with the tab. The body panel blocks must have unique name and must all be registered in the current registry (done here via the register attribute). This implies the current registry must be set (in this case, it is set as the Tabs registry).</tabbed>
<bar>Note the use of selectFill to set the background color of the tab when a tab is selected. Here the selected tab color is matched to the color of the associated body panel but it does not have to be.</bar>
#registry Tabs search display;
<tabbed window closable resize x=400 y=400 width=360 height=400 fill=wall title="Using Tabs" dEBUG>
    <body normalFont mRight=25 mBottom=15>
        <intro height=50 fill=white bordered mBottom=5>
            <heading="Tabs Example" flex center titleFont/></intro>
        <bar height=25 flex headerFont tabs=two>
            <one=first tabBODY=first bordered fill=lightGreen selectFill=green/>
            <two=second tabBODY=second fill=lightGreen selectFill=blue bordered/>
            <three=third tabBODY=third fill=lightGreen selectFill=red bordered/></bar>
        <bodies cards normalFont mBottom=5>
            <first="The first tab body" register bordered fill=green/>
            <second="The second tab body" register bordered fill=blue/>
            <third="The third tab body" register bordered fill=red/></bodies>
        <help describe=tabbed bordered height=100 fill=lightGreen;>

Note the value of the tabs attribute in the bar block is set to two. That sets the initially selected tab to be tab two. If the tabs attribute has no value, the default will use the first tab block (one in this case) as the initially selected tab.
